A British sea captain was behind bars on a remote island in Papua New Guinea last night after being arrested in connection with the sinking of one of his ships last year, in which 162 people drowned.

Peter Sharp, originally from the Shetland Islands, was ordered to surrender his British passport before being locked up on the island of East New Britain where he has been charged with 162 counts of manslaughter by criminal negligence.

He was also charged with sending an unseaworthy vessel, the 259 ton Rabaul Queen, to sea, before it sank off the coast of Morobe Province in February last year.

