The inquiry found that Mr Sharp had demonstrated that he had little or no respect for people, including those in authority.

Reports said that his 'gross disrespect' was reflected in the 'appalling and inhumane conditions' in which he was prepared to let passengers on the Rabaul Queen travel and might explain in part why he was prepared to compromise the safety of passengers on board his ships.

New Guinea Islands Divisional Commander Anton Billie said today that Mr Sharp was 'innocent until proven guilty and the matter is now before the courts.'

